rComments: Stuart seems to not care at all. He is always late and super disorganized. He obviously doesn't prepare for class at all and instead wants to lecture us about what he read in the newspaper when he should have been prepping for class. I wouldn't mind having a chat over coffee with him, but he is truly a terrible terrible professor.
Below average prof. He knows his stuff but cannot express himself well enough. Doesn't seem to care for his students. Hard to reach outside of class. Do not recommend.

Fun course, but he makes it boring. He will read articles in class to try to engage students, but spends very little time on the material. You can study all your notes for the final and midterm, but because his questions are so terrible, you will not do well.
teacherRatingTags: ['Tough grader', 'Lots of homework', 'Get ready to read']

rComments: not a fan at all. i took the AP version in high school and it was better than this. what he talks about doesn't add up with the textbook (he makes up names for things that are not referred to by that anywhere else). the lectures not fantastic and he doesn't wear a microphone. no practice questions, no warning for quizzes/hw. would not recommend.

I feel for him because a lot of students skip his lectures because they tend to be a bit monotone and not very engaging, but a lot of the stuff in his lectures causes more confusion and its very unclear.

Very understanding guy that works with you if you don't understand something. He genuinely knows his stuff and encourages questions so don't be shy. As far as the textbook goes, I never bought it and did well. If you've never taken an econ course before, you should revise the basic Macro concepts online early in the semester(I used Khan Academy).

rComments: A great professor, always responded quickly to emails. I learned a lot from his lectures. Would often post news articles on lecture topics for discussion which was great for understanding the concepts. He encourages discussion and participation. There's participation marks and pop quizzes, so you must attend. Tricky exams but a fair grader.

rComments: This prof assigns way too much work. The class was 6 weeks and there were constant assignments and quizzes that barely reflect what we learn in class. Its as if he doesnt prepare his lectures ahead of time because he just rambles. He is TERRIBLE at answering questions, and often it is unclear whether or not he is correctly solving the problems.

Prof will have pop quizzes and give homework assignments during lectures, an then won't post about their existence on bright space so if you don't go to class you won't be able to hand them in. Reads off his slides and is not great at answering questions.
teacherRatingTags: ['Graded by few things', 'Beware of pop quizzes']

rComments: Course average was 6 in fall 2018. Note there were weekly quizzes that were conducted online and required a code to complete and thus yours or a friend's attendance. The quizzes were worth 5% plus another 5% written down as participation. Difficulty aside, I would agree with all 3 comments below me.

Assignments are pretty easy but the midterm and final is very hard. the lectures are so boring. The feedback is not useful at all. Im sure he knows his stuff but very bad at explaining. If you are taking this as a elective to boost up your grade, AVOID! unless you are good at learining everything by your own with no help from the lectures.

This class made me cry. There were weekly quizzes, but they were barely related to what we'd covered in class. No matter how hard I tried to understand what he was explaining, I just could not get it. I emailed him a question, he told me to ask in class, but the explanation was rambling and left me googling the answer. I'm scared of my final grade.

Dr. Glosser is new to the University of Ottawa. He is very fair and does a good job conveying the material. His exams are very straight forward 20-25 MC + a couple short answer. His multiple choice questions are tough--you need to know your stuff. He offers a lot of ways to receive marks (midterms, bi-weekly assignments, quizzes, participation).
